    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Does the age of Cabernet Sauvignon affect food pairing choices?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, significantly. Young Cabernet Sauvignons with firm tannins pair best with grilled meats and bold flavors that can stand up to the wine's structure. Aged Cabernets with softer tannins and developed tertiary flavors work beautifully with more nuanced dishes like braised short ribs, mushroom risotto, or aged cheeses. The wine's evolution from fruit-forward to earthy complexity should guide your pairing choices.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should you pair Napa Valley and Bordeaux Cabernet Sauvignon differently?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely. Napa Valley Cabernets are typically fruit-forward and full-bodied, making them ideal for grilled steaks and barbecue with sweet or smoky sauces. Bordeaux blends tend to be more restrained and earthy, pairing better with classic French preparations like herb-crusted lamb or coq au vin. The Old World style calls for more subtle, traditional pairings, while New World Cabernets can handle bolder, more innovative flavor combinations.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best way to serve Cabernet Sauvignon for food pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve Cabernet Sauvignon at 60-65°F (15-18°C) and decant it 30-60 minutes before your meal to allow the tannins to soften. This temperature and aeration time helps the wine integrate better with food flavors rather than competing with them. Pour into large bowled glasses filled only one-third full to maximize aroma concentration, which is crucial for pairing success.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can you pair Cabernet Sauvignon with vegetarian dishes successfully?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, but focus on hearty, umami-rich vegetarian options that can match the wine's intensity. Grilled portobello mushrooms, eggplant parmigiana, or lentil-based dishes work exceptionally well. The key is choosing preparations with substantial texture and earthy or smoky flavors that complement rather than compete with Cabernet's bold character.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Cabernet Sauvignon food pairing good for beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Cabernet Sauvignon is excellent for beginners learning food pairing because it follows predictable rules: pair intensity with intensity. Start with classic combinations like Cabernet with steak or aged cheddar to understand how tannins interact with protein and fat. The wine's bold character makes successful pairings obvious, helping new wine drinkers develop their palate confidence before exploring more subtle pairing nuances.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the most common Cabernet Sauvignon pairing mistakes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is pairing young, tannic Cabernet with lean proteins without adequate fat or richness to balance the tannins. Another common error is choosing overly complex dishes that compete with the wine rather than complement it. Many people also serve the wine too warm or skip decanting, which prevents the wine from integrating smoothly with food flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">When should you choose Malbec or Syrah instead of Cabernet Sauvignon for food pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Choose Malbec when you want similar boldness but with more approachable tannins for dishes like grilled chicken or pork tenderloin. Opt for Syrah when your dish has smoky, peppery, or gamey elements that would complement Syrah's signature spice and earthiness better than Cabernet's cassis-driven profile. Both alternatives work better with dishes that need substantial wine presence but less tannic grip than Cabernet provides.</p>
